Modern Python versions (3.6+) have a memory performance optimization for dictionaries, where dict keys are shared between various class instances.<p>I am asking if plain Python&#x27;s dictionaries have the same optimization?<p>Given the two dicts with shared keys:
d1 = {&quot;name&quot;: &quot;Havoc&quot;, &quot;hand&quot;: &quot;left&quot;}
d2 = {&quot;name&quot;: &quot;Malice&quot;, &quot;hand&quot;: &quot;right&quot;}<p>Are &quot;name&quot; and &quot;hand&quot; shared between these two or does each one have a separate key inside Python&#x27;s memory pool?
